06529nam a22010215i 9783110733679DE-B159720230228015514.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20212021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107336797 a10.1515/97831107336792doi  a(DE-B1597)575191  a(OCoLC)1269268354  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aB945.S254bR43 2021 7aPHI0390002bisacsh04a19122300aReason, Justification, and Contractualism :bThemes from Scanlon /ced. by Michael Frauchiger, Markus Stepanians. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (X, 160 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLauener Library of Analytical Philosophy ,x2198-2155 ;v700tFrontmatter -- tBrief Book Overview -- tAcknowledgments -- tTable of Contents -- tInstead of an Introduction: Scanlon’s Project -- tDeontological Communitarianism. Laudation for Thomas M. Scanlon -- tContractualism and Justification -- tJustification Fundamentalism: A Discourse-Theoretical Interpretation of Scanlon’s Contractualism -- tOn How to Explain Rational Motivation: Where Internalism and Externalism Meet -- tMoral Reality and Moral Progress -- tEquality of Opportunity and Justified Inequalities: How the Family Can Be on Equality’s Side -- tImproving Scanlon’s Contractualism -- tSubstantive Responsibility and the Causal Thesis -- tResponses to Forst, Mantel, Nagel, Olsaretti, Parfit, and Stemplowska -- tWords of Thanks -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book collects major original essays developed from lectures given at the award of the Lauener Prize 2016 to T. M. Scanlon for his outstanding oeuvre in Analytical philosophy. In "Contractualism and Justification," Scanlon identifies some difficulties in his theory and explores possible ways to deal with them. In "Improving Scanlon’s Contractualism," D. Parfit recommends revisions and extensions of Scanlon’s theory, while R. Forst suggests in "Justification Fundamentalism" that Scanlon may want to replace reason with justification as his foundational concept. T. Nagel raises fundamental questions concerning "Moral Reality and Moral Progress," and S. Mantel offers in "On How to Explain Rational Motivation" a critical discussion of Scanlon’s cognitivist theory of motivation. Z. Stemplowska does the same for Scanlon’s conception of responsibility in "Substantive Responsibility and the Causal Thesis," and S. Olsaretti suggests in "Equality of Opportunity and Justified Inequalities" an alternative to Scanlon’s arguments against economic inequalities. All contributors receive extensive replies by Scanlon. For anyone interested in Scanlon’s seminal work in moral and political philosophy, the present volume is utterly indispensable.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aJustification (Ethics). 0aReason. 0aResponsibility. 4aKontraktualismus. 4aRechtfertigung. 4aT. M. Scanlon. 4anormativer Kognitivismus. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Analytic.2bisacsh  aScanlon, T. M.  acontractualism.  ajustification.  anormative cognitivism.1 aForst, Rainer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrauchiger, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMantel, Susanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNagel, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOlsaretti, Serena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParfit, Derek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScanlon, T. M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStemplowska, Zofia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov